                        <additions>
                            <list>
                                <item xml:id="a1">
                                    <desc type="GuestText"><title ref="LIT2849RepCh131"/>
                                        The note contains several corrections and additions in the margins, referenced in the body of the text by means of
                                        <foreign xml:lang="gez">tamallas</foreign>-signs (<locus target="#1v #6r"/>). It was written by <ref target="#h2"/>.
                                    </desc>
                                    <locus from="1v" to="7v"/>
                                    <q xml:lang="gez">
                                        <seg part="I">
                                            <hi rend="rubric">ሰላም፡ ለዝክረ፡ ስምከ፡</hi> ተጽውዖ፡ ዘቀደመ፡ በአፈ፡ አምላክ፡ አዳም፡ እንበለ፡ ይሰመይ፡ ስመ፡
                                            <hi rend="rubric">ሩፋኤል፡</hi> ምልዓኒ፡ ወወስከኒ፡ ዳግመ፡ መንፈስ፡ ቅዱሳዌ፡ አእምሮ፡ እንተ፡ ይፈሪ፡ ሰላመ፡
                                        </seg>
                                    <seg part="F">
                                        <hi rend="rubric">ሰላም፡</hi> ዕጣነ፡ ጸሎትየ፡ አዕርግ፡ እግዚኦ፡ ኀበ፡ አምላክ፡ ልዑል። በማዕጠንትከ፡ ዘፍያል፡ <hi rend="rubric">ሩፋኤል<supplied reason="omitted">፡</supplied></hi>
                                        ሊቅ<supplied reason="omitted">፡</supplied> ካህነ፡ ወንጌል። ወባልሔ፡ ኩነኒ፡ እምሕጕል።
                                        <hi rend="rubric">ኦአምላከ፡ ሩፋኤል፡ አድኀነኒ፡ እምነ፡ ሐጕል።</hi>
                                    </seg>
                                   </q>
                                </item>
                                <item xml:id="a2">
                                    <desc type="Inventory">
                                        The note is written in Arabic on the inner side of the back board. It mentions the textual contents of the book. Few words are not easily readable.
                                    </desc>
                                    <q xml:lang="ar">
                                        مديح... لمار روفايل الملاك
                                        سيرة الانبا اراݣاڨى... الرهبنة
                                        الانطونية في الحبشة وجدول
                                        تسلسل الرهبان
                                    </q>
                                </item>

                                <item xml:id="e1">
                                    <desc>A white sticker is glued to the inner side of the front board. The signature ‘MS. Eth. E.U. VI’ and the title ‘Za-Mikael Aragawi’ are printed on it.</desc>
                                </item>
                                <item xml:id="e2">
                                    <desc>Scribal corrections are rare: omitted letters or words added above the line (e.g., <locus target="#10va #20rb #61rb"/>), and erasures
                                        (e.g., <locus target="#10va"/>). The text on <locus target="#68vb"/> has been written in condensed script to accommodate the end of the column.
                                        Pen trial on <locus target="#1r"/>.
                                    </desc>
                                </item>
                                <item xml:id="e3">
                                    <desc>The names of the original owners, mentioned in supplications throughout, have been erased and replaced with those of
                                        <persName ref="PRS14037Zamaryam"/> (e.g., on <locus target="#15va #48ra #66va"/>) and <persName ref="PRS14039Enzira"/> (<locus target="#64ra #66va"/>),
                                        introduced by the epithet <foreign xml:lang="gez">ፍቁሮሙ፡</foreign> "their beloved".
                                    </desc>
                                </item>
                            </list>
                        </additions>

                        <bindingDesc>
                                 <binding contemporary="non-Ethiopian false">
                                   <p>The manuscript is not bound according to the traditional Ethiopian technique. The presence of a pair of unused sewing holes demonstrates
                                     that the present binding is not the first binding and the codex was rebound.</p>
                                     <decoNote xml:id="b1" type="bindingMaterial">
                                       The book is bound in <material key="cardboard">cardboard</material> boards fully covered with <material key="parchment">parchment</material>.
                                     </decoNote>
                                     <decoNote xml:id="b2" type="Boards">
                                       The boards have squares and are larger than the book block.
                                     </decoNote>
                                       <decoNote xml:id="b3" type="Cover">
                                         Full parchment cover undecorated.
                                       </decoNote>
                                       <decoNote xml:id="b4" type="Endbands">
                                         Stuck-on endbands obtained from a cord of neutral colour.
                                       </decoNote>
                                     <decoNote xml:id="b5" type="SewingStations">4</decoNote>
                                     <decoNote xml:id="b6">
                                       The manuscript is sewn continously on two cord sewing supports, which indicate the Western origin of the binding.
                                     </decoNote>
                                     <decoNote xml:id="b7" type="Spine">
                                       The quires do not present holes close to the head and and tail which may indicate the former presence of quire tackets.
                                       The titles of the texts in the manuscript are tooled in gold on the spine of the cover.
                                     </decoNote>
                                 </binding>
                             </bindingDesc>

